Junior Achievement Nigeria (JAN) in partnership with Lagos Business School (LBS) via its Venture in Management Programme (ViMP) has equipped 50 outstanding members of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC) with business, management skills. The 20th edition of the ViMP funded by African Capital Alliance Foundation (ACA Foundation) and Total E&P Nigeria Staff Multipurpose Cooperative Society Limited was a one-week intensive mini-MBA programme introducing the selected corps members to the different facets of managing a business, making crucial business decisions and developing skills for management. The academic director of ViMP of the Lagos Business School, Uchenna Uzor, said that the distinguishing feature of the programme is that it will help in addressing that section of the Nigerian population that is suffering from unemployment and underemployment, where the current statistics of those who are 15 – 35 years old, 55 per cent are currently unemployed. He said the programme will help people who are interested in starting/running their own businesses or working for existing businesses to acquire the basic life and managerial skills that will help them succeed. The executive director, Junior Achievement Nigeria, Simi Nwogugu, speaking to pressmen said that the focus on youth corps is as a result of the high impact and strong social responsibility component of the programme as corps members are the closest to the job market and as such its necessity to produce and prepare the university graduates for successful entry into the business world. 